Based on my investigation, the failing test errors with "register overflow" at line 97: `class B:A static a=A def f() end static b=1 static c=A end`. The error occurs in compilation, specifically when a subclass with multiple static initializers references the inherited parent class.

ROOT CAUSE: `src/be_parser.c:1365-1380` (`class_static_assignment_expr`) and its interaction with `class_inherit` (`src/be_parser.c:1420-1429`). For `class B:A`, `class_inherit` calls `be_code_setsuper(finfo, e, &e1)` which runs `exp2anyreg` on the class expdesc `e` and then `free_expreg(finfo, e)` (be_code.c:858-862). After that call, the original class expdesc `e` (the one held in `class_stmt`'s stack) has been mutated and its temporary register conceptually freed, yet `class_block` keeps using that stale `e` for every subsequent `static X = …` initializer. Each `class_static_assignment_expr` does `e1 = *e` and then `be_code_member` → `package_suffix` → `exp2anyreg(c)`, which now allocates a new register on top of stack each time but never frees it (because the stale `e` still claims to be a non-ETREG / mutated type, so neither `setsfxvar`/`free_suffix` nor `free_expreg` ever reclaims the register that was bumped). Three statics in a subclass therefore leak ~3 registers per pass; multiplied across re-entries the freereg counter climbs past 255, tripping the check at `src/be_code.c:121`.

LOCAL FIX: In `src/be_parser.c`, after `be_code_setsuper(...)` inside `class_inherit`, restore `e` to its original ETLOCAL form so subsequent static initializers see a clean class descriptor. Concretely, snapshot `*e` before calling `be_code_setsuper` and write it back, e.g.:
```c
static void class_inherit(bparser *parser, bexpdesc *e) {
    if (next_type(parser) == OptColon) {
        bexpdesc e1, save = *e;
        scan_next_token(parser);
        expr(parser, &e1);
        check_var(parser, &e1);
        be_code_setsuper(parser->finfo, e, &e1);
        *e = save;            /* restore class expdesc */
    }
}
```
Equivalently, in `class_static_assignment_expr`, call `be_code_freeregs` to reclaim any temp register `package_suffix`/`setsfxvar` left behind, asserting `finfo->freereg` returns to its pre-statement value.

GLOBAL FIX: Make register accounting symmetric and self-checking. Wrap every statement-level expression in the parser with a `freereg` save/restore (snapshot `finfo->freereg` and `finfo->nlocal` on entry, assert equality on exit in debug builds) so any helper that takes a `bexpdesc*` cannot silently leak temporaries into the caller's frame. Additionally, make `be_code_setsuper` (and other helpers that mutate caller-owned expdescs as a side effect of code emission) take a `const bexpdesc*` for the persistent operand and use a local copy internally, so callers never have to defensively snapshot. This eliminates the entire class of "stale expdesc reused after a code helper mutated/freed it" bugs that compounds into register overflow under benign-looking source.
